<bibRefCitation id="757F4B36560C694FCB2802ED8724F987" author="Liu, L. &amp; Wang, Y. &amp; Li, H." box="[819,1075,1521,1548]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" pagination="119 - 137" refId="ref5167" refString="Liu, L., Wang, Y. &amp; Li, H. (2016) Taxonomic review of the genus Teliphasa Moore, 1888 from China, with descriptions of four new species (Lepidoptera, Pyralidae, Epipaschiinae). ZooKeys, 554, 119 - 137. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 554.6177" type="journal article" year="2016">Liu, Wang &amp; Li, 2016</bibRefCitation>
. Female genitalia (
<figureCitation id="89D52A42560C694FCD1102ED864EF987" box="[1290,1369,1521,1547]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–13" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1347,1371]" captionTargetBox="[174,1413,193,1313]" captionTargetId="figure-29@5.[159,1428,181,1323]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 11–13. Female genitalia of Teliphasa spp. 11, T. nubilosa; 12, T. hamata; 13, T. spinaejuxta sp. nov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577738" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577738/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
) with anterior and posterior apophyses of equal length; ductus bursae elongate, membranous; corpus bursae with a pair of signa, a large distal sclerotised process present.
</paragraph>
